# N-Queens — CUDA Implementation

GPU-accelerated N-Queens solver using iterative backtracking with shared memory optimization.

## Approach

1. **Pregeneration**: The CPU generates all valid partial placements up to a fixed depth (4–6 rows depending on N), exploiting symmetry to halve the work.
2. **GPU dispatch**: Each CUDA thread receives one partial and explores its entire subtree independently.
3. **Shared memory stack**: The backtracking stack lives in shared memory (~4 cycle access) rather than global memory (~500 cycles), eliminating the main bottleneck of iterative backtracking on GPU.
4. **Bank conflict elimination**: Arrays use transposed layout `[depth][tid]` so threads in a warp access consecutive addresses, avoiding shared memory bank conflicts.

## Performance (RTX 4050)

| N  | Time     | Solutions        |
|----|----------|-----------------|
| 15 | 0.037s   | 2,279,184        |
| 17 | 0.226s   | 95,815,104       |
| 20 | 67.4s    | 39,029,188,884   |

## Build
```bash
make
```

Requires CUDA toolkit. For non-RTX 4050 GPUs, change `-arch=sm_89` in the Makefile to match your architecture.

## Run
```bash
./nqueens_cuda
Enter n: 17
```
